He vs Xavier Activation function:

Why is changing 1 to 2 significant ?

👉 It changes the variance of activations flowing through layers
👉 That directly affects vanishing vs exploding gradients


🧠 What is being controlled?

Each layer does:

Z = XW

We want:

Var(Z) ≈ Var(X)

So signal neither:

shrinks ❌ (vanishing)

blows up ❌ (exploding)


🟢 Xavier (1/n)
Var(W) = 1 / n

Assumes:
👉 activation keeps values symmetrically distributed

Works for:

tanh

sigmoid


🔵 He (2/n)
Var(W) = 2 / n

Why 2?

Because ReLU does:

ReLU(x) = max(0, x)

➡️ kills ~50% of values

So:

Var(after ReLU) ≈ ½ Var(before)


🔥 The key compensation

He says:

"Since ReLU halves variance, double it at initialization"

So:

½ × (2/n) = 1/n effective

👉 variance stays stable


⚡ What happens if you DON'T change 1 → 2?
Using Xavier with ReLU:
Var(W) = 1/n

After ReLU:

Var shrinks → shrinks → shrinks

➡️ vanishing activations
➡️ dead gradients
➡️ slow or no learning

Using He with ReLU:
Var(W) = 2/n

After ReLU:

Var stays stable

➡️ healthy signal flow


🧪 Intuition (very important)

Think of each layer as:

signal × weight → passes through ReLU → loses half energy

So:

Xavier → doesn't compensate → signal dies

He → compensates → signal survives


🧠 Why this matters more in deep nets

In 2 layers → small effect
In 10 layers → huge effect

Because:

(½)^10 → almost zero


🔥 Your mental model

Initialization is about energy preservation across layers

Xavier → assumes no energy loss

He → corrects for ReLU energy loss


TL;DR

Xavier uses 1/n but He uses 2/n. ReLU kills ~50% of signal so this doubles variance to compensate and without it → activations shrink → gradients die


